  "prompt": "What is the value of [math]\\sqrt [i\\pi ] {-1}[/math]?",
  "response": "To evaluate the expression \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\), we can interpret it as \\((-1)^{1/(i\\pi)}\\). Here's a step-by-step breakdown:\n\n1. **Express \\(-1\\) in Exponential Form:**\n   \\[\n   -1 = e^{i\\pi + 2k\\pi i} \\quad \\text{for any integer } k\n   \\]\n   This uses Euler's formula, where \\(k\\) accounts for the multi-valued nature of the complex logarithm.\n\n2. **Raise \\(-1\\) to the Power \\(1/(i\\pi)\\):**\n   \\[\n   (-1)^{1/(i\\pi)} = \\left(e^{i\\pi + 2k\\pi i}\\right)^{1/(i\\pi)}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Simplify the Exponent:**\n   \\[\n   e^{(i\\pi + 2k\\pi i)/(i\\pi)} = e^{1 + 2k}\n   \\]\n   Here, \\(\\frac{i\\pi}{i\\pi} = 1\\) and \\(\\frac{2k\\pi i}{i\\pi} = 2k\\).\n\n4. **Principal Value:**\n   For the principal value (when \\(k = 0\\)):\n   \\[\n   (-1)^{1/(i\\pi)} = e^{1} = e\n   \\]\n\n5. **General Solution:**\n   Considering all integer values of \\(k\\), the expression has multiple values:\n   \\[\n   (-1)^{1/(i\\pi)} = e^{1 + 2k} \\quad \\text{for any integer } k\n   \\]\n   However, the principal value is \\(e\\).\n\n**Final Answer:**\nIts principal value is Euler\u2019s number e. In other words,\u202f\u221a\u2071\u03c0\u2009(\u20131)\u00a0=\u00a0e",
